<br />
<br />Yes, I was talking about saving within FDS games, games that in the US used battery backup or passwords.  50 years is not what I would consider "awesome archival" material, in fact, thats garbage.  Hard disks are prone to failure and in moderate/heavy usage will usually fail within 5 years.  I'm sure newer ones may have a slightly longer life expectancy, but in my past experience a hard drive is far from what I would consider an ideal archival medium.  Also, plop a magnet next to a hard drive and tell me how good the data holds up.  Besides, even if hard disks are magnetic, cassette tapes are garbage.  VHS and cassette tape quality goes to shit over the years and the more you play it, the quicker it degrades.    As for the BASIC thing, you are pulling that completely out of your ass, unless you have documents from Nintendo that clearly state thats what it was for, you don't know any better than I about what it was used for.  Also, I suggest you quit threadjacking about stuff you are pulling out of your ass, this is about Toaster NES, which, BTW, I think the top loader makes more sense as well.  I can see the original being called a "toaster oven" since toaster ovens (at least the ones ive used) have a tray that slides in and then you pull a door down over it, somewhat like the original NES.

		

