	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">atari2600a wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Well my theory (which would be backed up by the majority of readers) would be much more feasible than yours.<br /><br />Let's go w/ a nice round number for the transfer rate for the time, say...300 baud.</div><br />That's the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kansas_City_standard" class="postlink">Kansas City Standard</a> bit rate. This encoding uses 4800 cells per second and 16 cells per bit: 0011001100110011 for 0 and 0101010101010101 for 1. But I seem to remember the frequency modulation on Apple II tape being much faster than that, maybe 1000 baud. It and the Acorn encoded a 0 as 0011 and a 1 as 0101. But as Apple became fond of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Group_code_recording" class="postlink">group code recording</a> once the Disk II was introduced, I'd imagine that data could be packed even tighter with the tech of the era, as in the case of 9-track reel-to-reel tape with five cells per four bits, or 3840 kbps.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Now let's say you have an NROM-based famicom title w/ an 8KB CHR-ROM &amp; 16KB PRG-ROM. It would take over 1 1/3 minutes to load.</div><br />You might be off by a factor of 8. At 300 bps, loading 192 Kibit takes nearly 11 minutes. But even under 3840 bps GCR, loading would still take 51.2 seconds.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">This would also mean that Nintendo  would have to put an additional 8KB of RAM into the unit so the PPU can directly access CHR data.</div>
<br />But it would at least have been standard practice. Every other system with a port-mapped video chip, including the Colecovision and SMS, had CHR RAM. Some systems, such as the Commodore 64 and Apple II, had "unified" RAM that the CPU and video chip shared.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


